<TEXT>
latvians allege 70000 soviet troops are pouring 
into the baltic republics to skew the voting in the 
independenceminded republics elections in the coming weeks 
a soviet military commander indicated friday that the troops are 
coming into the baltics from czechoslovakia and wont be 
transferred that quickly 
proindependence activists are hoping to win majorities in the 
parliamentary elections in latvia and estonia on march 18 but both 
republics have substantial russian populations who may vote against 
independence candidates a substantial influx of soldiers who can 
vote wherever they are stations could change the balance of power 
the baltic republics of latvia lithuania and estonia already 
have heavy concentrations of troops reportedly one out of every 
eight people in estonia 
lithuanians already have elected a majority of proindependence 
activists to their parliament and runoffs are scheduled 
baltics military commander fyodor kuzmin told the latvian 
legislature friday that the soviet troops being withdrawn from 
czechoslovakia will be transferred to the baltics though not 
necessarily permanently reported anda anspoka of the latvian 
peoples front 
in his comments soviet commander kuzmin reportedly gave no 
timetable for the troops arriving in the baltics however the 
soviets have told the czechoslovaks they need 16 months to withdraw 
all 73500 soldiers because there is no housing for them and their 
families in the soviet union which has a chronic and severe 
housing shortage 
the first units consisting of 22 t62 tanks and 33 armored 
vehicles left czechoslovakia on monday 
peoples front representative janis jurkama said on finnish 
television friday that our information is that they are coming to 
latvia just before the elections and they would vote 
i tell you people are being very nervous and that is why a 
lot of letters have been coming to the supreme soviet legislature 
asking our deputies to express a very strong protest to moscow 
he said 
kuzmin told the latvian legislature that the troops were going 
to lithuania and estonia rather than latvia anspoka said 
disbelieving lawmakers decided to protest to moscow and request 
that no more troops be sent to the baltics she said 
the latvian legislature also passed a law removing judges from 
the control of the communist party a judgeship is now 
incompatible with membership in a political party the official 
soviet news agency tass reported 
the latvian parliament also created a state bank empowered to 
issue currency independent from the soviet ruble tass said 
</TEXT>
