<DOCNO> AP900303-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the elderly communists religious liberals 
and social reformers at sunset hall are used to being outnumbered 
but there arent enough left now even to keep the house open 
sunset hall a 36room spanishstyle home for retired radicals 
is being sold for 12 million to a developer who wants to convert 
it into an apartment complex ann maupin president of the board 
governing the home said friday 
residents of the home which is running an annual deficit have 
until march 22 to move out of the 14 residents age 77 to 99 
eight have no place to go or dont want to go the rest have made 
other plans 
its the loss of a very important peoples institution said 
sadie tomkin 89 who once managed the communist newspaper peoples 
world 
if this was a decent society this would never have 
happened she said 
sunset hall residents can count among their brethren former 
resident ruben burroughs editor of upton sinclairs newsletter 
during the socialists 1934 gubernatorial campaign others helped 
form the union backbone for blue collar workers in the united 
states in the 1930s and some fought mccarthyera blacklisting in 
the 1950s 
founded in 1924 by the first unitarian church of los angeles 
sunset hall was designed to house religious liberals the home is 
funded primarily by residents monthly fees and has operated at a 
deficit for almost two decades said administrator thomas e 
brandlin 
it is expected to post an estimated 95000 deficit this year 
its worst ever he said 
residents pay between 900 and 1400 a month although some are 
charged less because of need 
were almost broke brandlin said a big chunk of money 
might help for a while but what sunset hall really needs is to be 
filled up with 30 paying residents 
we need enough residents to bring in 75000 per year or 
fundraising added mrs maupin but thats fundraising at a 
very high level 
she said there are 12 members on the board that governs the 
home with two who want the home to remain open the board is 
elected by the 240 members of the sunset hall nonprofit corp 
which is open to anyone who pays a 35 fee 
to fight the closure attorney kent ten brink said he intends to 
seek a court injunction blocking the planned sale 
residents some who must use canes and walkers have 
participated in recent years in demonstrations in support of the 
los angeles teachers strike and a picket by eastern airline 
workers 
and they say they may fall back on a timeworn strategy and stage 
a demonstration outside sunset hall which features a large 
treeshaded patio a library and a living room equipped with a 
grand piano the day they get evicted 
we have people here who expressed their thinking on world 
events and took part in them said drusilla falk im about the 
youngest here im 78 and when i arrived here four years ago i 
thought maybe i wont have to make any more moves 
waldemar hille wally to friends said the band of old rebels 
is not taking news of the closing lying down 
im a musician by trade and not accustomed to getting mad but 
we do have a lot of people here who are said hille who plays 
piano organ and a little guitar when hes able 
im going to try and keep my place here and quite a few other 
members will too he added but we dont expect miracles 
the 82yearold hille used to accompany singer paul robeson and 
was once a collaborator with folk singer pete seeger he said he 
moved to sunset hall about two years ago 
hille feared that without the intellectual stimulation provided 
by the home some residents may just fade away 
as a musician i can write and practice my instruments hille 
said i can stay alive at least other people arent as fortunate 
as that and they have only to look forward to a single apartment 
some place 
</TEXT>
