<DOCNO> AP900303-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
black market currency dealers on their 
sidewalk trading floor outside a train station are scrambling for 
east german marks as the nonconvertible currency soars against the 
wests mighty deutsche mark 
germans from both countries and the regions 
wheelinganddealing poles who trade on the black market are facing 
a run on the east german mark amid speculation over a pending 
monetary union between the germanys 
talks are under way on a plan to introduce the west german mark 
as legal tender in east germany and some east german officials 
have called for a 1to1 exchange rate at the outset 
that proposal has brought a sudden switch at the sidewalk 
trading spot 
you can hardly get east marks these days it was a lot easier 
only a week or two ago although the exchange rate is a lot better 
now for sellers said one dealer who identified himself only as 
harald k 
the 24yearold east german who deals in west berlin on his 
days off from the army said east germans a month ago had to pay 20 
east marks for one west mark 
now they can buy one shiny deutsche mark coin for only a green 
5east mark note 
when east germanys communist government opened the berlin wall 
in november the boom in traffic between the nations boosted 
business on the sidewalk exchange in front of the train stop at the 
zoo in west berlin 
a few west germans bought east marks to travel east and buy 
cheap staples like rice pasta and fresh meat or dine like kings 
at subsidized restaurants but most customers were east germans out 
hunting for consumer goods unavailable back home 
now though east marks are in demand and more west germans are 
buying in the hope of turning a quick profit when the nations 
economies are merged as part of a monetary union 
west german chancellor helmut kohl has proposed the union as a 
first step to unification of the countries some west german 
officials also say that east germanys economy is crumbling and 
will collapse without the union 
people are expecting with a currency union the east german 
mark will be exchanged at a 1to1 rate said reinhard pohl a 
monetary expert at west berlins german economic research institute 
pohl said some west germans are trading their convertible 
deutsche marks at the favorable black market rate then depositing 
them with friends or relatives in the east and hoping for the 
favorable exchange rate once economic union is announced 
the east mark has surged 30 percent against the deutsche mark at 
currency trading offices in west berlin and frankfurt and in 
vienna austria and zurich switzerland 
uncertainty over how economic unification will be carried out 
also has made west german stock and bond markets jumpy 
the markets are being driven by emotion speculation and 
politics and thats not going to change before the elections in 
east germany on march 18 said one frankfurt bond trader who spoke 
on condition of anonymity 
he said west germanys masscirculation bild newspaper had 
contributed to the speculation friday with a report that east 
german and west german finance officials have agreed to a currency 
union by july 1 
bild said a joint currency commission had decided that east 
germans savings which alone amount to 17 billion east marks in 
bank accounts would be exchanged over an unspecified period of 
time at a 1to1 rate 
for savings that couldnt be swapped immediately for lack of 
ready cash west german interest rates would be paid bild said 
only savings deposited in east german bank accounts before jan 
1 or possibly before nov 9 when the berlin wall was opened 
would be converted it added 
the paper said cash of up to 1000 marks could probably be 
exchanged at a 1to1 rate but that larger amounts would be cashed 
at a less favorable rate 
the east german government declined to comment and the west 
german bundesbank denied the report saying no decisions would be 
made on the conversion rate before the election 
</TEXT>
