<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900303-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
using a computerdriven descendant of the player 
piano a music scholar gave new life to more than 100 rare george 
gershwin solos recorded on piano rolls 
it is as if you are being treated to a live performance in 
your living room the scholar artis wodehouse of san francisco 
said friday as she showed off the technology that saved the songs 
gershwin recorded the pieces on rolls for player pianos between 
1916 when he was 17 and 1926 player pianos were the jukeboxes of 
their day wodehouse said and most of the gershwin performances 
were his elaborate arrangements of then popular songs eighteen 
were his original compositions 
sheet music for his compositions and for his arrangements of the 
other pieces did not survive 
wodehouse a pianist herself found 105 of the 120 piano rolls 
through a michigan collector in 1988 she then found a computer 
firm microw distributors inc of butler nj that had developed 
a technology that turns piano rolls into a format computers can 
read 
microw put the gershwin rolls on floppy disks that can be 
played on synthesizers or a computerdriven update of the player 
piano the yamaha disklavier 
on friday the gershwin songs emanated from a disklavier in a 
performance at yamahas communication center in new york 
gershwin would love it wodehouse said he would be 
tickled with the technology he was a great believer in the new 
and he would have been delighted to learn that people still cared 
about his music 
gershwin one of americas greatest composers and a piano 
virtuoso died in 1937 his first big claim to fame came in 1919 
with the release of swanee but his position in the annals of 
music history was secured in 1924 by rhapsody in blue 
a few years ago wodehouse transcribed sheet music for several 
old 78 rpm gerswhin records i went over and over them she 
said it took about 150 hours to transcribe a threeminute 
piece because his arrangements were so elaborate 
when those pieces were published she became wellknown among 
gershwin lovers and about a year ago she won a national endowment 
for the arts grant to study gershwin piano rolls 
microw had just created a technology that could read the piano 
rolls which wodehouse compares to long pieces of toilet paper with 
little pin pricks in them player pianos read the rolls by blowing 
air through the holes triggering hammers inside the pianos 
the computer data was made by taking pictures of images of light 
aimed through the holes and putting that data onto disks she said 
wodehouse then persuaded the coda music software co to adapt 
its music transcription program finale to transform the microw 
disks into sheet music seven of the original gershwin compositions 
found on the rolls are scheduled to be published by warner bros 
she said 
if all 18 of the gershwin works are published it will more than 
double the existing gershwin solo sheetmusic repertoire wodehouse 
said plans also are in the works to create recordings of the 
gerswhin rolls 
player pianos fell into disuse during the depression when they 
were hacked up for scrap wood and replaced by record players 
the disklavier which can be used as a conventional piano as 
well as a minirecording studio that will tape and recreate 
whatever is played on it ranges in price from 7000 to 22000 
the disks are sold by microw 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900303-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the government is forcing airlines to open the 
skies to the handicapped but says blind people still cant sit 
near the exit door 
transportation department rules requiring more accommodations 
for the disabled on airliners brought immediate criticism from an 
airline industry trade group and from a national organization of 
blind people both said they were considering lawsuits 
the rules call for moveable aisle armrests and more space for 
wheelchairs and require airlines to make other provisions for 
handicapped travelers 
billed as an antidiscrimination measure required by congress 
the rules will cost airlines an estimated 400 million over the 
next 20 years for training personnel and modifying airliner 
interior design to accommodate more disabled people said don 
trilling dot director for regulatory affairs 
you dont treat handicapped passengers differently or force 
restrictions on them unless you have a very good safety grounds for 
doing it said bob ashby a department lawyer who briefed news 
media on the directives that will take effect in about five weeks 
all new airliners with more than 30 seats will be required to 
have moveable armrests on half the aisle seats and widebody 
planes generally those carrying 200 passengers or more must 
have at least one lavatory that can accommodate a handicapped 
passenger 
the rules also strictly limit airlines ability to refuse 
service to handicapped people prohibit any restriction on where 
they can sit except for safety reasons and prevent airlines from 
requiring handicapped passengers to be accompanied by an attendant 
if they do require it the airline must fly the attendant free 
these regulations will ensure that us air carriers provide 
consistent predictable service to disabled travelers without 
discrimination and with accommodations the passengers need said 
transportation secretary samuel skinner the regulations 
accomplish this goal consistent with the safety of all passengers 
the air transport association which represents us carriers 
said the requirements would diminish safety and service for air 
travelers and impose an unacceptable economic burden on the 
airlines and all their customers 
the trade group said requiring 50 percent moveable aisle 
armrests was way out of proportion with the real need to 
accommodate disabled passengers 
another provision that would give both manual and electric 
wheelchairs priority in main cabin storage areas will seriously 
diminish storage space for carryon items of other passengers 
ata said 
airliners built in 1992 or later will be affected and older 
aircraft will have to comply as their interiors are refurbished 
usually about every seven years 
the rules prohibit carriers from restricting seating on the 
basis of handicap except to comply with federal aviation 
administration safety regulations 
an accompanying faa rule limits seating in exit rows to 
passengers who can locate the door quickly follow instructions for 
its use physically open the heavy doors determine whether its 
safe to go out understand both verbal and handsignalled 
instructions from flight attendants and get around obstacles to 
lead other passengers off the aircraft 
tony broderick faa associate administrator said the rule was 
reached reluctantly but does not single out any group 
he said among those prohibited would be parents with small 
children people too frail to operate the door passengers with 
broken legs or other disabilities that would inhibit movement 
obese people and children under 15 as well as people who are blind 
marc maurer spokesman for the national federation of the blind 
said the rule continues a pattern of discrimination the 
department of transportation has permitted airlines to carry on for 
some time 
a bill is pending in congress that would allow blind people to 
sit wherever they want on airliners maurer said the group is also 
considering legal action 
blind people dont need anything in these rules except to be 
left alone maurer said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

