<TEXT>
an explorer on a dog sled trek across 
antarctica disappeared in a blizzard for 11 hours as foul weather 
threatened the teams plan to finish the first nonmechanized 
crossing of the continent by saturday 
keizo funatsu the japanese member of the sixman international 
team was found early friday after surviving a night of 70 mph 
winds and 20below temperatures by burrowing into the snow 
when he was found he was yelling im alive he was found 
in very good condition said jennifer gasperini headquarters 
spokeswoman for the minnesotabased expedition 
funatsu disappeared thursday after meeting with a french film 
crew that hauled a mobile home to the teams campsite 16 miles 
from their goal team members roped themselves together and 
searched for six hours they gave up because of darkness but found 
him in the morning after a twohour search ms gasperini said 
it wasnt known if funatsu would be able to complete the last 16 
miles of the trek to the soviet scientific station at mirnyy on 
the eastern antarctic coast under his own power 
the 1990 transantarctica expedition was stalled for a second 
day friday on the last leg of a 3800mile sevenmonth journey by 
dogsled and skis from western antarctica to the eastern coast on 
the indian ocean 
the wind dropped to 30 mph friday afternoon but conditions 
remained too hazardous to risk a final push ms gasperini said 
especially dangerous was a maze of ice crevasses along the route 
they had hoped to end the 11 million corporatesponsored 
journey by 6 am est saturday at mirnyy where they planned to 
meet television crews 
the expedition led by will steger of ely minn and jeanlouis 
etienne of france hopes to parlay interest in the feat into public 
support for preservation of antarctica and to lobby world leaders 
who are reviewing the 1961 antarctic treaty 
team members reached the south pole the halfway mark of their 
journey on dec 11 to become the first to reach the bottom of the 
world by dogsled since roald amundsen discovered the pole in 1911 
