<TEXT>
a bipartisan commissions plan to overhaul the 
nations health care system would provide private or public 
insurance coverage to all americans regardless of whether they can 
afford it 
however the plan already is drawing fire for failing to say how 
the 65 billion annual bill would be paid by taxpayers 
the proposals adopted friday by the us bipartisan commission 
on comprehensive health care are aimed at providing universal 
access to health care and assuring that the elderly and disabled 
will be able to receive care at home or in nursing homes 
sen jay rockefeller dwva chairman of the commission said 
the recommendations to congress respond to a crisis in us health 
care that leaves more than 31 million people without any health 
insurance and an additional 20 million with inadequate coverage 
he called it wrong outrageous morally repugnant that 
americans are denied care in emergencies 
we cant offer easy answers but we can offer a challenge to 
this country he said 
the panel voted 87 for the plan to achieve universal access 
and 114 for the longterm care plan the three members appointed 
by president bush divided 21 in favor of both proposals the other 
12 members of the commission are members of congress 
the commissions plan relies on both increased federal spending 
for health care coverage including a federal takeover of the 
medicaid system now shared with the states and private coverage 
in addition to its estimated 662 billion cost an additional 
20 billion would be paid by private businesses through increased 
contributions to employee health plans or to the public plan 
without a way to pay for it it is a nonstarter it is 
legislatively dead said rep fortney pete stark dcalif a 
member of the panel and chairman of the house subcommittee on 
health 
he criticized the bush administration for failing to provide 
leadership in finding a way to provide health insurance 
sen david durenberger rminn also a member said the plan 
failed to provide any restraints on health care costs 
its going to skyrocket our costs he said 
rockefeller said the plan would need a revenue source that could 
be counted on to increase by 8 percent to 9 percent a year 
automatically because of anticipated rising costs 
the plan would be phased in over five years in its first year 
health care coverage would be extended to all children and pregnant 
women 
the plan would require all businesses with more than 100 
employees to provide private health insurance to their workers or 
to contribute to a public plan for employees and nonworking 
dependents 
smaller businesses would be encouraged to provide insurance 
through tax credits and subsidies but might eventually be required 
to provide coverage if they did not meet targets by the end of the 
fiveyear period 
the longterm care plan would pay the full cost of the first 
three months in a nursing home by anyone regardless of income 
benefits for additional time in a nursing home would be improved 
permitting recipients to keep their homes and certain other assets 
the commission was created in 1988 when congress voted to expand 
medicare catastrophic care coverage that coverage was repealed 
last year after groups representing the elderly abandoned their 
support complaining about the cost 
the commission was called the pepper commission for its first 
chairman the late rep claude pepper dfla it was directed to 
recommend ways to assure health care and how to pay for it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

