<TEXT>
here are key points in the pepper commissions 
recommendations for health care 
the recommendations fall into two areas access to health care 
and longterm care 
accessequals 
businesses with 100 or fewer employees would be encouraged to 
provide health insurance for their employees and nonworking 
dependents tax credits and subsidies would be available and 
selfemployed and unincorporated businesses could deduct 100 
percent of premiums 
employers who buy coverage and achieve a specified coverage 
target would not be required to participate in the federal public 
health insurance plan 
all businesses with more than 100 employees must provide 
private health insurance for a specified package of benefits or 
contribute to the public plan for all employees and nonworking 
dependents 
the public plan would cover employees and dependents that 
contribute and nonworking individuals who buy in or are 
subsidized it would replace medicaid and pay providers according 
to medicare rules it would be financed and administered primarily 
by the federal government although states could opt to administer 
it 
the minimum benefit package includes primary and preventive 
care physician and hospital care and other services there would 
be costsharing with subsidies for lowincome people and limits on 
outofpocket spending 
at full implementation all americans would be required to have 
health insurance through their employer or the public plan 
the plan contains a provision that could require the secretary 
of health and human services to submit to congress a plan for 
insuring any remaining uninsured employees of small companies after 
five years 
longtermequals 
severely disabled people of all ages would be eligible for 
social insurance for home and communitybased care 
a nursing home program would be established providing 
protection so that no one must be impoverished before receiving 
covered longterm care individuals could keep their homes and 
30000 in assets couples could keep up to 60000 
the federal and state governments would share financial 
responsibility for the nursing home program the federal government 
would finance the home and communitybased care program and the 
first three months of care 
states are responsible for cost containment quality assurance 
and consumer protection 
private longterm care insurance fills gaps not covered by the 
plan subject to government standards 
</TEXT>
