<TEXT>
space explorers will have to use nuclear power 
on mars and the national science council says the united states 
should study employing nuclear rockets to get travelers to the 
planet 
in a friday report to vice president dan quayle the council 
acknowledged formidable barriers of public acceptance to the 
use of nuclear power in space 
however it said the use of such power eventually will be 
essential on both the moon and mars because of heavy energy 
demands 
it also recommended testing and possibly a demonstration in 
space of the feasibility of sending rockets to mars by nuclear 
propulsion 
the report analyzed a study done by the national aeronautics and 
space administration as part of president bushs initiative to put 
bases on the moon and mars early in the next century 
among its findings 
nasa needs to study the effects of longterm space flight on 
human beings because on the basis of present knowledge a 
multiyear exposure to weightlessness even with onboard exercise 
and countermeasures and an intermediate stay on the surface of 
mars presents unacceptable risks to the crew 
operation of a us space station by the late 1990s as 
scheduled is a reasonable assumption but plans for the station 
are not adequate for a moonmars mission the station may not be 
the most appropriate staging base for the moon and mars and it is 
possible that an additional station will eventually become 
necessary 
although the nasa proposals envision bases on mars it 
appears that a station in mars orbit requires a less demanding 
infrastructure than a surface base and might serve a useful purpose 
in the early stages of human space exploration 
possibilities for international cooperation should be explored 
because breakthroughs have been made in europe japan and elsewhere 
and most importantly the ussr has substantial relevant 
capability demonstrated continued interest in mars and an 
apparent strong desire for cooperation with the us in mars 
exploration 
the councils study made by a 14member committee named in 
january said nuclear rockets would reach mars in onehalf to 
onethird the time needed for singlestage chemical propulsion 
systems unmanned spacecraft have made the 111 million mile voyage 
to mars in six months 
the use of nuclear technology in space faces formidable 
barriers of public acceptance however especially if employed in 
earth orbit the council said therefore issues of safety are 
paramount in research and development 
it said one type of nuclear technology known as the nerva 
class is available for fullscale development and should be 
evaluated for injection to mars in competition with hydrogenoxygen 
chemical systems 
if careful systems studies show a significant advantage 
for nuclear rockets in trip time or in weight to orbit an inspace 
demonstration of this technology should be done as soon as 
possible the council said 
it will not be feasible to select the nuclear rocket as a 
baseline in a system architecture until such a demonstration has 
been conducted 
after announcing the moonmars initiative july 20 the 20th 
anniversary of the first moon landing bush asked quayle chairman 
of the national space council to explore ways of carrying it out 
nasa made a 90day study and quayle asked the national research 
council an arm of the congressionally chartered national academy 
of sciences to evaluate it 
