<TEXT>
economic hard times gripping third world 
countries have created dire conditions for women and impeded 
efforts to wipe out sex discrimination and exploitation un 
experts and activists say 
there has been some progress worldwide in life expectancy for 
women declines in infant mortality and improvements in 
nutrition said vivian lowery derryck president of the 
africanamerican institute in new york 
but when you get to the equality issues the picture is 
starkly gloomy she said 
deteriorating economic conditions have forced women to turn to 
begging prostitution and other quasilegal and illicit 
activities in india peru and several african nations according 
to a unicef study 
the observance of international womens day on thursday and 
related activities worldwide will focus more attention on work to 
promote equal rights for men and women 
the un commission on the status of women meeting this week in 
geneva has concentrated on political and economic obstacles facing 
women with a special interest in areas affected by armed conflicts 
or foreign intervention 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar in a special 
address to mark international womens day plans to call for a 
renewed global commitment to improve conditions for women 
both men and women must work together as equal partners in 
order to ensure a sustainable future for the generation to come 
the un chief says in a prepared statement 
recent un reports stress there is much more work to do 
poor women have become poorer more women are poor and women 
are now poorer in relation to men one un report says 
through their hard work they try to ensure the survival of the 
poorest segments of the population but at great cost to themselves 
this drain on womens time resources and energy also inhibits 
their ability to participate in political life and hence in having 
an influence in changing the policies which affect them so 
adversely the report adds 
economic problems also have diminished opportunities for young 
women particularly in latin america and africa 
the crisis has diminished educational and economic 
opportunities for young women thus affecting their future ability 
to contribute to society on an equal basis with men the un 
report said 
a unicefsponsored study on mexico found that the economic 
crisis had worsened conditions for women particularly in rural 
areas because families could no longer survive intact in the 
countryside young women were forced to migrate to find work 
the report by unicef said women were pulled off the land to work 
as day laborers where they had no social benefits lived in sheds 
and were easy targets for sexual abuse and for those women left on 
the farms there was more work to do the report said 
another unicef study concluded that at least onethird of the 
population with the lowest incomes in latin america and the 
caribbean has been kept afloat by poor women working harder and 
longer hours 
unicef research has found that brazilian mothers because of 
their increased responsibilities in coping with the financial 
crisis of the 1980s are experiencing greater mental health 
problems those women feel doubly guilty for the plight of 
their families the unicef study says 
activists point out there are significant signs of progress 
in eastern europe south africa and central america you can 
see that its the all boats rising with the tide phenomenon ms 
lowery derryck said women can see change and it empowers them 
now we need to capitalize on these changes 
