scientific advisory panel which drew up the list of compounds that 
must bear the labels under proposition 65 had incorrectly exempted 
numerous products from the 1986 initiative 
robies decision finalized a tentative ruling he issued last 
fall in a lawsuit brought by environmentalists and labor groups who 
argued that deukmejian was seeking to sidestep the regulations 
approved by voters 
robie said the state had created an improper exemption for 
selected industries without specific regard to the chemicals 
involved 
if upheld on appeal his ruling could force food drug and 
cosmetic companies to evaluate thousands of products to determine 
if they pose a significant chemical risk if that determination is 
made proposition 65 requires that those items carry a warning 
label 
companies will have to spend millions analyzing their products 
to show that they pose no significant risk said peter hutt a 
washington lawyer representing the grocery manufacturers of america 
steven berzon an attorney representing the coalition that 
challenged the deukmejian administration said robies ruling 
goes 100 percent in our favor 
proposition 65 the socalled clean water initiative requires 
warning labels on substances that pose a significant risk for 
cancer and birth defects 
the standards established by proposition 65 are stricter than 
those set by the us food and drug administration and in 
interpreting the initiative state officials initially said fda 
standards could be used for at least 20000 consumer products 
