they urged rejection of the tanker skippers claim that evidence 
about his ships potential sinking is irrelevant 
hazelwoods lawyers contend it was impossible for the skipper to 
move his giant tanker off the reef once it was stuck there and 
thus it makes no difference whether he tried to move it they seek 
to bar evidence on what might have happened if the ship moved 
the state seeks to bolster the speculation of expert witnesses 
on the subject by showing jurors the results of accident 
simulations suggesting the tanker was in danger of capsizing or 
sinking 
the 43yearold hazelwood from huntington ny is charged 
with criminal mischief reckless endangerment operating a vessel 
while intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil he could receive 
7 years in prison and fines of 61000 
the exxon valdez ran aground on bligh reef on march 24 spilling 
11 million gallons of crude oil into prince william sound the 
spill killed countless birds fish and other marine animals and 
blackened hundreds of miles of rocky shoreline 
a key element in the charges against hazelwood is recklessness 
and assistant district attoney brent cole is seeking to prove that 
the skippers alleged efforts to try moving the ship constituted 
recklessness 
according to a legal definition he has read to jurors a 
person acts recklessly when the person is aware of and 
consciously disregards a substantial and unjustifiable risk 
it continues the risk must be of such a nature and degree that 
disregard of it constitutes a gross deviation from the standard of 
conduct that a reasonable person would observe in the situation 
to be found guilty of second degree criminal mischief the 
felony the jury must determine that hazelwood recklessly risked 
the property of another in an amount exceeding 100000 thus the 
prosecution must prove recklessness and risk 
captain hazelwood is arguing that because it was impossible 
for the exxon valdez to come free there was no risk involved 
said the prosecutions legal memorandum but it added the issue 
is not whether it was possible for the vessel to come free but 
whether captain hazelwoods mistakes in not realizing the vessel 
was firmly aground and not recognizing the danger in refloating 
were reasonable 
