<TEXT>
us and south korean military 
engineers cut through nine feet of granite today to unearth a 
tunnel allegedly dug by north korea under the demilitarized zone 
separating the two koreas 
the tunnel was discovered in a remote mountainous border area 
called punchbowl the site of a fierce battle between us and 
communist troops during the 195053 korean war 
breaking through shouted onlookers as engineers with giant 
drills and earthmoving equipment succeeded in reaching the tunnel 
in seoul defense minister lee sanghoon told a news conference 
the tunnel located about 100 miles northeast of the capital is 
a southward tunnel that can be used forinvasion 
the tunnel is the fourth to be found since 1974 
but lee said his ministry believed there were more than 20 being 
dug by north korea inside the 25milewide 155milelong dmz one 
of the most heavily armed borders in the world 
south korean officials claim north korean leader kim il sung 
ordered the tunnels built to infiltrate communist troops behind 
south koreas first defense lines north korea has denied digging 
any tunnels 
a statement issued by the usled united nations command said 
the tunnel was apparently dug by north korea to invade the 
south 
it said the tunnel was six feet high and six feet wide large 
enough for three armed soldiers to run through it side by side a 
full regiment could pass through the tunnel in an hour officials 
said 
the manmade tunnel is 430 feet beneath the surface the defense 
minister said he said its length and age were not yet known 
in view of the changing global situation and our sincere peace 
initiatives the construction of such a tunnel into our area across 
the truce line is a serious violation of the armistice agreement 
and an intolerable act of aggression lee said 
he urged north korea to stop provocative acts of aggression 
and help pursue ways to cut tensions on the divided korean 
peninsula 
col ht linke spokesman for the united nations command said 
the tunnel was first detected after a us army investigation team 
drilled into a tunnellike cavity on christmas eve 
closer observation confirmed the probability that a tunnel 
existed and work to confirm suspicions began dec 30 1989 linke 
said this also confirmed our belief that north korea has 
constructed other tunnels across the frontline linke said 
south korea found three tunnels allegedly dug by north korea 
across the border in 1974 1975 and 1978 two of them were 
discovered near the truce village of panmunjom 35 miles north of 
seoul 
a third tunnel found in 1978 near panmunjom was dug through 
granite nearly 500 feet below the surface and extends 1300 feet 
into south korean territory across the border it has been open to 
the public 
the korean peninsula was divided into the communist north and 
the capitalist south in 1945 after world war ii north korea 
invaded south korea in 1950 to start the threeyear korean war the 
two countries remain technically at war despite sporadic dialogue 
they remain arch enemies no unauthorized travel or communication 
is allowed between citizens of the two sides 
