<TEXT>
a small black axe hangs just inside the door to 
veniamin gaufbergs apartment reinforcement strips glisten in the 
doors frame 
the gaunt 69yearold jew who fought the nazis in world war ii 
is preparing for a new battle against racial attacks 
if they open the door ill cut off their fingers what else 
can i do asked gaufberg 
although not all have resorted to axes gaufberg is typical of 
soviet jews anguished by what they say is a resurgence of 
antisemitism dating back centuries like record numbers of his 
countrymen gaufberg has had enough and is planning to leave his 
homeland for good something he vowed he would never do 
i have one goal now to survive until the day i leave he 
said in the western moscow apartment he shares with four relatives 
jewish writers have been beaten antijewish graffiti has 
appeared and hatemongers openly distribute leaflets that borrow 
from hitler to condemn the zionist menace and call for attacks 
on jews 
even the official press has carried blatantly antisemitic 
articles 
alexander bushkov wrote in the newspaper krasnoyarsk komsomolets 
last june that jews in the soviet leadership participated in all 
the cases of genocide against the russian people 
no recent mob violence against the soviet unions 14 million 
jews has been reported but rumors and threats of pogroms or 
organized racial attacks are instilling a strong sense of danger 
even panic 
it has added to a jewish exodus of unprecedented proportions 
aided by easier soviet emigration policies about 71000 soviet 
jews left last year the highest annual total since the 1967 middle 
east war began a new wave of emigration nearly 5000 left in 
january 
everyone i know is planning to run away wherever possible 
said gaufberg 
the situation is so intolerable every day i feel it said 
roza gutman a 23yearold jew from the crimea huddled in a crowd 
of wouldbe emigres at the us embassy in moscow waiting to learn 
whether she and her family would be allowed to enter the united 
states she explained the forces driving them away 
she entered a moscow music teachers college because she felt 
that as a jew she stood little chance of being accepted at the 
more prestigious conservatory but today there is greater danger 
than discrimination 
gutman said she is considering buying a gun to protect herself 
from threats which she said included vandalism to her dormitory 
room and shouts from classmates to clear out of our country 
its become so acute that every sunday my friends say there 
will be a pogrom and dont go out she said 
now its simply dangerous theres an elementary threat to 
life she said 
in december the soviet unions first national jewish congress 
in decades condemned the orgy of antisemitism sweeping the 
country and said it was causing an unprecedented panic among the 
jewish population 
president mikhail s gorbachevs liberalization drive has been a 
mixed blessing for soviet jews it has allowed freer emigration and 
the opportunity to practice their religion and culture without 
official harassment but it has also allowed russian nationalists 
to speak out in some cases with antisemitic messages the 
worsening economy and political upheaval of gorbachevs rule have 
caused many soviets to look for scapegoats and jews have been 
prime targets 
some jews like gutman suspect highlevel complicity in 
antisemitism but can offer little proof the record of the 
countrys previous rulers however is far from clean 
czar nicholas i said in 1816 nine years before ascending the 
throne that jews were fullfledged leeches and his regime 
portrayed jewish traders as exploiters of the masses czarist 
forces either stood by or participated in beatings murders and 
looting of apartments of jews in pogroms of the 1880s and early 
1900s 
after the soviets took power with strong support and 
participation of jews jews no longer were confined to a section of 
russia known as the pale and although it was poorly enforced a 
1918 decree signed by soviet founder vladimir lenin outlawed 
antisemitism 
his successor josef stalin however launched a campaign 
against cosmopolitanism after world war ii in which jews were 
arrested and executed 
the official soviet encyclopedia boasted in 1953 that soviet 
policy led to the disappearance of the jewish question but 
antisemitism continued jews faced discrimination in education 
jobs and the practice of their religion 
the government has been accused to taking a lax attitude toward 
the threats authorities have countered with a propaganda campaign 
of their own 
the regional communist party chief in odessa went on television 
in late january to report that a commission condemned nationalist 
and chauvinist activity in the black sea port which has a large 
jewish population leaflets quoting hitlers mein kampf and 
calling for jewish pogroms had been spread in odessa 
in moscow the interior ministry said rumors of impending 
pogroms are unfounded and that soviet press articles reporting the 
threats mislead the public and can serve to promote ethnic strife 
and destabilization 
the strongest official response has been the filing of criminal 
charges of inciting national and racial hatred and strife 
against pamyat the russian nationalist group linked to the wave of 
antisemitism the weekly newspaper literaturnaya gazeta said the 
charges were filed after pamyat published a statement that said in 
part jews and their relatives must not be allowed to defend 
dissertations to acquire knowledge and get academic titles to 
join the soviet communist party 
