<TEXT>
congress and the white house are all but 
certain to make changes this year in the grammrudman 
deficitreduction law which has dominated debate over the federal 
budget since its enactment in 1985 
if the revisions are major it would be the second time in its 
short life that the legislation designed to gradually force a 
balanced budget has been substantially altered 
the changes will at the very least be forced by an issue that 
lawmakers have been fixated on in recent weeks the gigantic 
surpluses accumulated each year by the social security trust fund 
but with grammrudmans declining annual deficit targets 
scheduled to expire in fiscal 1993 when the budget is supposed to 
be balanced there are other crosscurrents as well 
conservatives want to extend the deficit targets into later 
years to hold down spending for domestic programs liberals want to 
eliminate the targets soon so that social spending can expand and 
they want to have the pentagon budget and taxes play a greater role 
in cutting the deficit 
there are about 100 ideas in this place about how the process 
will be changed says senate budget committee chairman james 
sasser dtenn 
the driving force for the changes is the evergrowing social 
security surplus expected to be 74 billion next year alone 
critics and its become hard to find members of congress not 
sharply critical say this surplus makes the overall federal 
deficit appear smaller than it actually is easing the political 
pressure to address the budget shortfall 
the congressional budget office projects the deficit for fiscal 
1991 which begins oct 1 at 138 billion take out the 
retirement funds and the shortfall would be 212 billion 
almost everyone on capitol hill believes lawmakers will act this 
year to remove the social security surpluses from the deficit 
calculations 
we believe we should separate the social security trust funds 
from the budget and we will enact the legislation to do so 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash said last week 
but that raises another problem 
grammrudman already requires that the federal deficit be sliced 
by about 37 billion next year unless the laws target is raised 
as seems likely removing social security surpluses from the 
arithmetic would force lawmakers to find 111 billion in savings a 
task considered politically impossible and risky to the economy 
a certain set of dominoes begin to fall here says house 
budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif if the first 
decision is to move social security off grammrudman calculations 
that inevitably leads you to confront what you do with the 
remaining large deficit 
more complex proposals to change the law are also under 
consideration but all share a common element the retirement 
systems surpluses would no longer be included when the deficit is 
added up 
sasser and panetta have each offered their own plans both of 
which would put off some of the fiscal pressure republican 
congressional leaders are working with the white house on a gop 
alternative other members of both parties also have submitted 
legislation 
the target of all this is a law enacted in the middle of the 
reagan administration when the conservative president and 
democrats in congress fought to repeated budget standoffs 
with deficits growing out of control they peaked at 221 
billion in fiscal 1986 grammrudman was enacted a series of 
declining deficit targets were set leading to a balanced budget in 
1991 failure to reach the shortfall goals triggers automatic 
spending cuts on most federal programs 
congress and the white house initially lowered the deficit 
somewhat but havent made steady progress the law was eased in 
1987 to stretch out the targets to 1993 but domestic spending has 
grown and presidents reagan and bush have blocked tax hikes and 
sharp defense cuts 
critics charge that budget writers in the capitol and the white 
house have not really become adept at cutting the deficit only at 
finding loopholes around grammrudman and ignoring real deficit 
reduction 
a desirable change would be to put a dynamite charge under 
grammrudman and blow it up says henry aaron senior fellow at 
the brookings institution 
but supporters say it has focused attention on the governments 
red ink and helped force savings one of the laws authors sen 
phil gramm rtexas says the legislation should be kept alive 
until the budget is balanced 
i didnt do all this flirting just to get down to the altar 
and not get the i dos said he said 
