<TEXT>
during last weeks closeddoor bargaining over 
a senate clean air bill negotiators haggled over countless numbers 
but the most important number was never mentioned 
it was 60 the number of senators needed to make a compromise 
clean air bill filibusterproof and assure its senate passage 
in the months ahead through the 22 days of negotiations the number 
hung over the meeting room like a blanket of smog 
the agreement between senate leaders and the bush administration 
over clean air legislation was a major victory for senate majority 
leader george mitchell dmaine who instigated the closeddoor 
discussions in early february 
he will bring the bill to the senate floor for action on monday 
but while there is expected to be lively debate and attempts to 
make changes the bill likely will not be altered significantly 
the secretive negotiations criticized by environmentalists 
publicly and some senators privately were a masterful exhibition 
of legislative maneuvering and the principal goal according to 
various officials involved was to produce a bill that would not 
become the victim of regional interests on the senate floor as 
clean air legislation so often had in the past 
for years sen robert byrd dwva when he was majority 
leader blocked clean air bills regularly because controls on acid 
rain would threaten thousands of jobs in the highsulfur coal 
mining areas of his state much of the midwest and parts of the 
south rely on highsulfur coal to fuel electric power plants the 
source of most of the sulfur dioxide emissions that cause acid rain 
a bloc of 14 senators primarily from the midwest and headed by 
byrd had threatened to stall passage of legislation again spurred 
by word from utilities across the midwest that the tougher 
pollution controls would be far too costly for many of the plants 
that dot the region 
meanwhile there also were factions in the senate worried about 
other parts of the clean air bill as approved by the environment 
and public works committee senators from the west and parts of the 
south were worried that the pollution controls would inhibit future 
growth the auto industry lobbied the white house against the 
bills tough automobile emission controls enlisting sen carl 
levin dmich to argue their case in the closeddoor 
negotiations and manufacturers buttonholed anyone they could to 
tell them of the high cost of proposed controls on toxic chemical 
releases 
the dilemma facing mitchell was how to eliminate enough of the 
concerns in the bill to forge an alliance strong enough to overcome 
whatever opposition remains for that he needed the support of the 
white house 
so the private negotiations began 
the provision on controlling toxic chemicals was weakened and 
small businesses and industrial sources were exempted from 
smogcausing pollution controls the bush administration was now 
ready to accept both of those parts of the bill 
the battle then turned to dealing with the chief objections of 
the auto industry 
a provision that would have required automakers to increase the 
fuel efficiency of their cars was jettisoned early but agreement 
on auto emission controls which were targeted by the 
administration as too expensive proved to be more difficult 
mitchell trying to get the talks moving set a deadline saying 
if no agreement could be reached hed take the legislation to the 
floor anyway but the administration held some important cards as 
well without the support of the president mitchell might not have 
the votes to overcome a midwest filibuster 
white house chief of staff john sununu sent that message when 
after meeting with mitchell he suggested a rush to push the bill 
to the floor without agreement on automobile emission controls 
could be undermining the acid rain section 
so after several days of marathon meetings that lasted past 
midnight an accord was reached on the automobile issues a second 
round of controls were significantly weakened so that they may 
never go into effect 
mitchells strategy was about to bear results 
the legislation now had the support of president bush who in 
turn could be counted on to produce enough republican votes that a 
filibuster likely would be overridden no matter what the midwest 
senators did 
but there were still some loose ends 
the concerns of the senators from the west and parts of the 
south over the impact of the acid rain controls on future growth 
had to be dealt with for if they allied themselves with the 
midwest in for different reasons opposing the bill its chances 
were slim 
a provision was crafted to deal with the problem by giving 
socalled clean states additional pollution allowances to better 
handle future growth that brought another bloc of senators into 
line 
as the discussions on acid rain began the senators from the 
midwest and byrd from west virginia were now alone and outgunned 
we did not have a choice between the good the bad and the 
ugly we had a choice between ugly uglier and ugliest said sen 
christopher bond rmo recalling his travail during the private 
negotiations on acid rain 
when the compromise agreement was announced byrd said he would 
continue to seek some changes on the senate floor but rejected the 
possibility of a filibuster 
we all have to be reasonable men and women he explained 
mitchells strategy had worked 
</TEXT>
