<TEXT>
joan claybrook is banking on the story of 
charles keatings lincoln savings and loan to persuade voters to 
demand changes in the way congressional elections are financed 
public citizen the organization claybrook leads is among a 
number of selfstyled public interest groups pushing congress to 
accept public financing of the campaigns with spending limits and 
significant restrictions on political action committee donations 
a new poll conducted for public citizen shows a clear majority 
of the public 58 percent supports the concept of public financing 
the highest level since just after the watergate scandal 
but the poll also found most voters know very little about the 
mechanics of public financing and are skeptical that any financing 
system would remove the influence of political action committees 
formed by special interests 
that is where claybrook hopes the story of keating and the 
widespread problems in the savings and loan industry will help 
the collapse of keatings lincoln savings and loan will cost 
taxpayers 2 billion and claybrook estimates that the 150 billion 
federal bailout of the sampl industry overall is costing each 
taxpayer about 1000 
the poll found overwhelming anger among voters who were told 
about five senators who intervened on keatings behalf with federal 
regulators who were considering seizing lincoln because of 
questionable lending and investments 
keating and associates previously had donated 600000 to the 
campaigns of causes of the five senators 
that anger according to the pollsters could provide public 
citizen and its allies with the opening they have always needed to 
persuade the public that the campaign financing system should be 
overhauled 
the scandals surrounding the savings and loan industry in 
particular have created a political moment where voters are able 
to make the conceptual link between campaign money and their own 
interests and quality of representation the analysis from the 
pollsters said 
the pollsters cautioned however that while people are unhappy 
with the current campaign finance system and increasingly skeptical 
of congress they will be difficult to mobilize 
the public though increasingly unhappy with the current 
system examines the issue through its larger political lenses 
which do not focus easily on campaign finance as a political 
issue the analysis said 
public citizen and its allies have little time to redirect the 
focus 
congressional leaders have promised to bring campaign finance 
legislation to the floor this spring but no bipartisan agreement 
is in sight and both democrats and republicans bickering among 
themselves 
lobbyists for public citizen common cause and other groups are 
increasingly skeptical that their proposals will be enacted 
the groups are hoping that a groundswell of public support will 
improve their chances and the public citizen poll contained 
evidence to convince them that a well orchestrated campaign could 
attract supporters 
most encouraging to the groups was poll data showing that 58 
percent of respondents favor the concept of public financing the 
highest level of support since immediately after the watergate 
scandal 
seventyfour percent said the congressional campaign system 
needs to be changed and 18 percent said the system is a mess and 
needs to be fundamentally reformed 
majorities supported several goals of the groups including 
limits on political action committee contributions overall 
campaign spending limits and a requirement that candidates raise 
most of their money in their home district or state 
also drawing wide support were proposals to provide each 
candidate with a fixed amount of television time and reduce mailing 
rates in return for promises of limited spending 
the public is saying that it wants congress back said 
claybrook 
yet the poll provided indications as well that there are tough 
obstacles to rallying the public behind campaign finance reform 
the nationwide poll of 1100 probable voters last month found 
campaign finance far from the top of the list of chief concerns 
just 5 percent ranked it first ahead of other issues such as drugs 
and crime the economy taxes and the environment 
the poll also found that support for public campaign financing 
the centerpiece of the changes sought by public citizen and its 
allies withered when voters were reminded their tax dollars could 
be used for negative attack ads or for support of extremist 
candidates 
the public interest groups are adopting a number of strategies 
designed to convince voters that the faults of the current system 
should outweigh their reservations about public financing 
common cause long a critic of the use of money from political 
action committees is getting personal releasing detailed lists of 
every pac donation accepted by incumbent members of congress over 
the last decade 
the us public interest research group a longtime advocate of 
clean air legislation on saturday released an analysis showing 
that pacs tied to companies and unions opposing the legislation 
have donated 274 million to senate and house candidates in the 
past decade 
for its part public citizen is combining its lobbying of 
congress with targeted field work hoping to raise public awareness 
of the issue in the districts of lawmakers who are seen as 
impediments to reform 
weve never failed to name names said claybrook 
in the poll 53 percent of respondents said they would vote for 
a challenger who supported public financing if the incumbent voted 
against it the pollsters said that reaction was probably greatly 
overstated but it still shows voters are in an antipolitical 
mood at least in part because they feel congress is more 
responsive to financial backers than constituents 
