<TEXT>
for friends and foes of the newly licensed 
seabrook nuclear power plant visions of the future are as 
different as the twin reactors on the site one licensed and 
ready the other rusty and unfinished 
seabrook operators and nuclear industry proponents see the 
completed reactor poised to generate electricity for up to 1 
million new englanders 
opponents see the corroded containment dome of seabrooks second 
unit as a beacon of their fight and the nations antinuclear 
movement 
by the time the nuclear regulatory commission granted seabrooks 
operating license on thursday the twinreactor plant proposed in 
1972 with a pricetag of less than 1 billion had evolved into a 
65 billion single reactor and pushed its lead owner public 
service company of new hampshire into bankruptcy 
critics have promised to appeal the nrc decision once the 
appeal is filed the us court of appeals in washington would 
decide whether the reactor can operate while the legal fight 
continues 
the focus of the court battle will be the federally required 
emergency response plans for 17 new hampshire and six massachusetts 
communities within 10 miles of the reactor seabrook is two miles 
from the massachusett line 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis became seabrooks most 
prominent antagonist in 1986 when he refused to submit emergency 
response plans for the six massachusetts communities saying safe 
evacuation was impossible 
the nrc subsequently accepted evacuation plans drafted by 
seabrooks operators 
its correct to say there has never been a case where the 
court has overturned an nrc license but its also correct to say 
that there has never been a license issued which has been so 
legally vulnerable said massachusetts attorney general james 
shannon who plans to file an appeal along with antiseabrook 
groups in new hampshire and massachusetts 
two appeals already were pending in washington even before the 
full commission approved the licensing 
arguments have been set for april on appeal of the nrcs 
decision to grant seabrook a lowpower license last may and the 
nrc licensing boards nov 9 decision to authorize a fullpower 
license also was appealed 
while plant foes look to the courts seabrook operators are 
trying to move beyond history 
in an interview friday edward brown president of seabrooks 
operator new hampshire yankee was weary of debating the merits of 
the evacuation plans 
brown instead said he would seek to mend fences with neighbors 
including some new hampshire communities that had opposed the 
plant 
we have and will continue to try to get them to work with 
us he said its a matter of taking a conciliatory approach 
not of ignoring the issue 
brown said he anticipated cooperation even from massachusetts 
once the plant was operating 
also dominating browns future is the actual startup he said 
he expects glitches and shutdowns as the reactor embarks on its 
two to threemonth process that will bring the plant to 100 
percent power 
we can expect during the fullpower ascension unless it goes 
absolutely flawlessly which would be unusual there are times 
when we will take the unit off line to do some adjustments he 
said 
a court victory for plant opponents is not in his vision of the 
future 
theyve tried it before brown said and failed 
