security forces clashed saturday with activists 
claiming election fraud in the asian republic of uzbekistan and 
some demonstrators were killed local activists and official 
sources said 
one activist said up to 30 people died but an official said 
fewer than 10 were killed 
abdurashid sharif a spokesman for the uzbekistan grassroots 
organization berlik said internal security soldiers opened fire on 
a crowd of up to 3000 peaceful demonstrators in the city of 
parkent about 30 miles from the regional capital of tashkent 
he said an angry crowd then stormed the local police 
headquarters and set it on fire it also broke the windows of the 
regional communist party headquarters sharif said 
speaking in a telephone interview from tashkent he said the 
activists were protesting alleged fraud in feb 18 elections and 
demanding the resignations of elected officials 
sergei v kharitonov a spokesman for the soviet interior 
ministry in moscow confirmed there was a clash in parkent a city 
of about 200000 people sharif who visited parkent with other 
berlik officials quoted local doctors as saying up to 30 people 
were killed by gunfire by soldiers and police but kharitonov said 
in a telephone interview that both sharifs figure and an estimate 
of 10 dead given by another parkent resident were too high 
kharitonov said he could not give a figure 
he said there was no curfew in parkent and interior ministry 
soldiers were withdrawn following the afternoon clash the city was 
reported calm late saturday 
moslem central asia is the latest region of the soviet union to 
suffer ethnic violence as president mikhail s gorbachev loosens 
decades of tight kremlin control last month 22 people were killed 
in rioting in dushanbe the capital of neighboring tadzhikistan 
republic 
in addition tensions remain high in the caucasus republics of 
armenia and azerbaijan to the west where hundreds have been killed 
in the past two years 
sharif said the initial gathering in parkent developed 
spontaneously without being called by berlik or any other group 
he charged that interior ministry soldiers were bussed from 
tashkent and opened fire to break up the peaceful crowd there 
were no aggressive acts on the part of the residents of the city 
before the soldiers attacked he said 
