<TEXT>
the exxon valdez with 10 of her tanks 
spouting oil was an immovable object when her skipper called out 
orders to move ahead according to expert witnesses in joseph 
hazelwoods trial 
which brought up the question can someone be convicted of 
trying to do something which is impossible 
the three witnesses whose expertise is costing the state of 
alaska about 90000 were not hired to comment on the impossiblity 
of getting the tanker off bligh reef after it went aground that 
was a defense point 
the consultants came to tell jurors that hazelwood charged with 
felony criminal mischief in the nations worst oil spill was 
reckless when he gave the order to start the engines because he 
risked capsizing or sinking the massive vessel 
but defense attorneys michael chalos and dick madson used their 
crossexaminations to suggest there was no such risk because the 
exxon valdez was firmly impaled and wasnt going anywhere 
like most legal issues the socalled impossiblity doctrine 
is a subject of debate and interpretation 
in newly filed legal briefs the prosecution contends that 
hazelwoods intentions are the paramount issue because he didnt 
know in the darkness of march 24 1989 whether his ship was 
capable of moving 
captain hazelwoods reliance on the impossibility doctrine is 
misplaced because the issue is not whether it was possible for the 
vessel to come free but whether captain hazelwoods mistakes in 
not realizing the vessel was firmly aground and not recognizing the 
danger in refloating were reasonable said the prosecutions 
brief 
the argument was offered in support of a prosecution plan to 
present the results of accident simulations showing the scientific 
probabilities of the tanker capsizing or sinking after the 
grounding 
the 987foot tanker which left valdez with a full load of 
alaska crude oil struck the jagged reef at the entry to scenic 
prince william sound its tanks were gashed spilling nearly 11 
million gallons of oil thousands of birds fish and wildlife were 
killed and black goo coated hundreds of miles of rocky shore 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny is charged with the felony 
and three misdemeanors reckless endangerment operating a vessel 
while intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil 
witnesses have said that hazelwood gave orders to restart the 
engines and move ahead several times they say he gave rudder 
orders which changed the ships heading but it didnt budge 
you dont know if the vessel was capable of moving even one 
inch do you chalos asked expert george kirk greiner jr 
obviously it wasnt said greiner it didnt move 
robert beevers a former tanker captain was adamant in his 
testimony that hazelwood risked further damage to the ship by 
trying to move it 
but what if it simply couldnt move asked madson 
thats what happened said beevers that doesnt mean 
he wasnt trying to get it off at that point 
the third witness salvage expert william milwee jr said 
hazelwood was reckless in trying to move the tanker because he 
didnt have enough information about the ships position 
i think it was reckless because captain hazelwood did not have 
enough knowledge of the situation to attempt an immediate 
refloating he said 
chalos confronted milwee with calculations of the tankers 
engine horsepower and the ships grounded condition 
there is absolutely no question this ship would not have moved 
using its engines alone said milwee 
no matter what captain hazelwood did asked the lawyer 
no matter what captain hazelwood did said the witness 
but captain hazelwood did nothing to try to determine that 
he continued to assert that hazelwood was reckless 
with the defense scheduled to open this week hazelwoods 
lawyers plan to present their own computer simulations of the exxon 
valdez accident and they will call experts in an effort to hammer 
home their impossibility theory 
but they are not abandoning their original position of why 
hazelwood gave the orders to move ahead they say he was trying to 
stabilize the tanker on the reef 
