iranian president hashemi rafsanjani on 
saturday promised economic reform and called for boosting 
industrial production to ease economic hardship that has prompted 
protests according to news reports 
rafsanjanis office also set up a 24hour hot line to handle 
complaints in the face of public frustration after a decade of 
economic troubles revolutionary turmoil and an eightyear war with 
iraq 
iranians are contending with soaring inflation shortages of 
almost all basic commodities and high unemployment all in part 
due to the war with iraq a ceasefire was reached in august 1988 
tehran radio monitored in nicosia quoted rafsanjani as saying 
saturday the only solution for economic problems and 
revitalizing the society is to increase production 
speaking to managers of staterun industries most of which are 
operating at a loss he said we do not have political cultural 
or military difficulties currently our difficulties are mostly 
from a shortage of production 
sources in tehran reported a number of angry protests last week 
caused by popular resentment over continued economic hardship 
the mujahedeen khalq an opposition group claimed security 
forces killed several hundred protesters there has been no 
independent confirmation of that claim 
rafsanjani blamed high prices on middlemen saying they take 
advantage of the governments foreign exchange shortfall to import 
goods and sell them at exorbitant prices 
he acknowledged that keeping the iranian rial artificially 
inflated at 70 to the dollar was at the root of the economic 
problem 
the price of imported goods when converted into rials are 
prohibitively expensive and beyond the reach of most of irans 55 
million people 
the government offers the goods at a much reduced price at a 
loss to itself the subsidized imports however are too small in 
number to meet growing demand 
rafsanjani said it is not advisable to continue the past 
policy and provide all goods with the 70rial exchange rate even 
if there is sufficient foreign exchange to do so 
he added that what will save the country is that consumer 
goods are produced inside the country and are offered to the 
people at reasonable prices 
he said the countrys reliance on imported goods must be reduced 
rafsanjani said in january that factories were operating at 40 
percent of capacity 
since his election july 28 he has tried to boost the private 
sector to increase investment and encourage foreign investment to 
revitalize the economy 
but his efforts have been frustrated by antiwestern 
fundamentalist radicals in the tehran hierarchy who advocate a 
totally nationalized industry and oppose foreign investment 
rafsanjani has advocated the privatization of inefficient state 
industries which account for most of the 1 billion deficit 
projected in the 57 billion budget for the coming year 
