belongings of those who acknowledged they had been fishing the 
sherburnes contended on appeal that the fact they had gone fishing 
did not give authorities probable cause for a search 
they called the stop a violation of their constitutional rights 
but the maine supreme judicial court rejected their appeal in a 51 
vote 
justice robert w clifford writing for the majority agreed 
with the trial court that the roadblock was conducted reasonably 
he said the states interest in preserving game and fish outweighed 
the intrusion on motorists who were stopped and fishermen who were 
searched 
the dissent came from justice caroline d glassman who accused 
the majority of a faulty analysis of constitutional law ms 
glassman said catching a few fishing violations did not warrant the 
use of the roadblock 
the sherburnes attorney robert e sandy jr of waterville 
said late friday afternoon that he and his clients accepted the 
courts decision 
we have been given a full and fair hearing before the highest 
court in the state sandy said we lost the decision 
</TEXT>
