<TEXT>
it would be a lot easier to understand the state 
of the us economy right now if things like the weather didnt 
keep blurring the picture 
for the past few months nearly all the statistical information 
on economic activity has come out amid a chorus of qualifications 
analysts said the numbers for december showed misleading 
strength in industrial production for example because frigid 
temperatures in much of the country swelled demand for heat and 
electrical power 
in january it was reported retail sales figures were 
artificially inflated by a sudden swing to abovenormal warmth that 
drew shoppers out of their homes 
thus by the time a 11 percent upsurge in the consumer price 
index for january was announced a few weeks ago numerous 
explanations had been prepared to show why it shouldnt worry 
anyone 
if you excluded food and energy costs which are said to be 
especially prone to deceptive shortterm fluctuations the cpi was 
up a less threatening 06 percent 
to those who still found the latter figure disturbing observers 
cited further special influences including an increase in public 
transportation fares in the new york city area 
the idea of screening out supposedly aberrant influences makes 
sense in principle after all analysts who study the numbers are 
looking for trends of lasting significance when you are watching 
for changes in the tide you dont want to be distracted by 
individual waves 
still there may be limits to how many asterisks and footnotes 
an average citizen might accept 
veteran riders of the new york city subways for instance will 
have trouble swallowing the idea that what they encountered at the 
start of 1990 was a onetime fare increase 
twentyfive years ago they recall a trip cost 15 cents now it 
is 115 
similarly consumers might balk at the idea that their actual 
experience with inflation is better portrayed if you dont count 
the cost of feeding their families or driving their cars 
inflation is a general rise in the price level says paul 
boltz financial economist at the investment management firm of t 
rowe price associates it can occur even while prices of some 
goods are falling 
likewise prices of some goods can rise more rapidly than the 
general inflation rate but subtracting them out of the inflation 
measure does not lower inflation 
the idea that the weather has somehow been abornally wild and 
wacky this winter also is suspect true temperatures have 
fluctuated widely day by day and week by week from their historical 
averages but those things tend to even out 
as of early this month cumulative degreeday counts for the 
season in the northeast were running very close to those of last 
winter at the same time and to normal levels calculated by 
meteorologists 
many economic observers hold out the hope that a better fix on 
the economy will be available soon now that winter is almost over 
but evidently those bets are off if we have some sort of 
unusual spring 
