<TEXT>
each year manufacturers belch thousands 
of tons of chemicals into the stratosphere eating the fragile 
ozone layer that protects the earth against the suns damaging 
ultraviolet rays 
until last year the clear skies over ibms circuit board plant 
in endicott in southcentral new york belied the plants identity 
as one of the largest users of ozonedepleting chemicals in the 
united states releasing more than 2 million pounds of the 
invisible chemicals annually from its white steel pipes 
but in january international business machines corp announced 
that after spending millions of dollars and years of research the 
plants emissions of ozonedepleting chemicals had been reduced 
almost 75 percent 
in the face of growing evidence that industrial chemicals are 
eroding the ozone that filters ultraviolet rays ibm is one of a 
number of american companies slowly beginning to change the way 
they do business 
the destructive effects on the ozone caused by 
chlorofluorocarbons used as refrigerants cleaning solvents and to 
make bubbles in plastic foam have been known for more than a 
decade 
the environmental protection agency has ordered a 50 percent 
reduction in the use of cfcs by the end of the century and many 
companies have set earlier deadlines or pledged to phase them out 
altogether 
but according to the national resources defense council 
emissions of two chemicals that are as yet unregulated methyl 
chloroform and carbon tetrachloride together account for 33 
percent of the manmade ozonedestroying chlorine in the 
stratosphere 
as long as they are used the ozone will be unable to recover 
even if cfcs are phased out entirely the washingtonbased 
environmental interest group says 
spokeswoman deborah sheiman said the group is particularly 
concerned about methyl chloroform a chemical used primarily as a 
metal cleaner and degreaser which has not been widely acknowledged 
as a threat to the ozone 
most of the attention has been on the cfcs sheiman said 
were hoping to turn that around we believe that methyl 
chloroform has got to be controlled if were going to repair the 
damage to the ozone hole 
although about 200 companies reported reduced methyl chloroform 
emissions in 1988 the latest year for which figures are available 
almost as many increased emissions sheiman said 
at ibms vast 88building complex in endicott the company uses 
methyl chloroform in production of computer circuit boards 
in 1987 and 1988 the plant emitted more than 1 million pounds 
of methyl chloroform about 2 percent of the total amount of the 
chemical used at the plant environmental engineering manager 
dennis f whittaker said 
last year ibm substituted a waterbased solvent for methyl 
chloroform in one production line resulting in an 89 percent 
reduction in methyl chloroform emissions down to 121000 pounds 
whittaker said 
the new process which ibm is implementing at plants in texas 
japan and west germany was developed after more than five years 
collaboration between ibm engineers and suppliers whittaker said 
he estimated the cost of research development and engineering 
changes at about 40 million 
it takes a long time and its a tremendous investment he 
said its not something you do to improve your profit line 
methyl chloroform still is used in the companys advanced 
technology line where more complex boards for mainframe computers 
are produced ibm has not found a substitute precise enough to use 
in that process whittaker said 
were working on it he said we need a breakthrough its 
hard to schedule an invention 
pratt amp whitney of east hartford conn reported the highest 
methyl chloroform emissions in the country in 1987 the aircraft 
engine manufacturer has committed to reducing those levels by 80 
percent to 90 percent in the next four years by switching to 
alkaline cleaners spokeswoman peggy kay said 
the companys emissions already dropped by more than 75 percent 
in 1988 she said 
but kay said it takes years of testing to ensure that changes 
made in the companys manufacturing processes do not hurt the 
product 
you have to make sure that youre producing the same 
quality she said if not then its not worth it you want 
safe aircraft engines 
companies switching to environmentally safer alternatives find 
they do not always work as well as methyl chloroform 
the johnson controls plant in watertown wis has replaced 
methyl chloroform with a petroleumbased solvent plant engineer 
russell miller said 
ive gotten lots of complaints he said methyl chloroform 
is a very good solvent but its very environmentally wrong he 
said 
at the fischer controls international plant in marshalltown 
iowa alkaline washers are replacing methyl chloroform as a 
degreaser said ron allen the plants director of loss prevention 
the new washers are more expensive and difficult to use but 
much friendlier to the environment allen said 
we are optimistic that we can make alkaline washers work as 
well he said we have a strong formal commitment to the 
environment and we feel we need to be pacesetters for our 
customers 
the national resources defense council wants to see laws banning 
the use of methyl chloroform but in the meantime public pressure 
is pushing some companies to begin voluntarily reducing emissions 
of ozonedepleting chemicals sheiman said 
i think its having an impact she said that so many 
companies have come forth with these pledges it certainly has 
seemed to resonate in corporate boardrooms 
</TEXT>
