<TEXT>
nordstrom inc put on a pedestal for delivering 
extraordinary service at its department stores may have had an 
unfair advantage over the rivals that have long looked up to the 
retailer 
some of the smiling salesmen and women known for writing 
personal thankyou notes to customers and going to unusual lengths 
to satisfy shoppers apparently have been scowling inside outsiders 
who saw a happy family of nordies now are learning they may 
have gotten the wrong impression 
the seattlebased department store owner virtually admitted this 
past week that employees hadnt been fully paid for providing the 
impeccable service that has made nordstrom famous 
the company said it created a 15 million reserve for backpay 
claims a provision that eroded fourthquarter earnings 
for the quarter ended jan 31 earnings tumbled 34 percent to 
314 million or 39 cents a share from 475 million or 58 cents a 
share a year earlier sales rose 12 percent to 8575 million in 
the quarter from 7651 million 
much of the drop in quarterly earnings reflected higher 
merchandise markdowns to keep up with pricecutting competitors 
accusations have come to light that nordstrom pressures its 
employees into performing tasks on their own time 
the washington state department of labor and industry ruled last 
month that nordstrom had a pattern of making sales clerks work 
during offhours without compensation and ordered the company to 
pay them for uncompensated hours employees sometimes bring 
merchandise to customers homes thank them in writing for shopping 
at nordstrom and do other good retailing deeds 
making matters worse nordstrom has been hit with two 
classaction lawsuits one filed by three shareholders claiming 
they and others who own company stock suffered financial losses 
because nordstrom officers failed to disclose the labor problems 
kurt barnard a new yorkbased retail consultant says now that 
nordstroms dark secret is attracting national attention 
competitors may feel less inclined to emulate the company 
by not paying fully for the work it got out of employees a 
company its competitors considered the epitome of retailing 
excellence actually had an unfair advantage 
their competitors have been under tremendous pressure to 
render the kind of service that nordstrom has been so famous for 
he said the question now arises will they be able to render the 
same type of service if they have to pay for it will other stores 
still be so eager to follow suit 
even before nordstroms dirty laundry began being aired in 
public the companys stock had been taking a beating the stock 
40 percent owned by the founding nordstrom family has slumped 
about 35 percent since reaching a high of 4250 a share over the 
summer it was trading around 27 last week 
some analysts poohpooh the idea that the bad publicity over 
nordstroms labor practices will cause lasting damage to a stock 
with heaps of potential 
richard pyle of the investment firm piper jaffray amp hopwood 
inc says now is an ideal time to invest in nordstrom 
were comfortable recommending the stock as a buy for people 
looking to own a longterm growth company pyle said the only 
time you get to buy this company cheaply is when its in the midst 
of a minicrisis 
a severe case of inventory bloat in 1984 and the stock market 
crash in october 1987 provided two earlier buying opportunities he 
said 
the traits that he admires in nordstrom havent been altered 
the company is a savvy fashion merchandiser and produces sales of 
more than 400 a square foot roughly double the volume of its 
competitors 
pyle predicts the labor issue will be resolved satisfactorily 
in any case not all nordies are negative on the company as a 
support rally at the companys flagship seattle store last thursday 
attested 
nordstrom has 60 stores in washington oregon california 
alaska virginia and utah it plans 16 more with expansion into 
illinois new jersey maryland minnesota indiana connecticut 
massachusetts and new york 
there are a lot of employees out there who are supportive of 
how nordstrom runs its business said pyle adding that there are 
plenty of real estate developers all over the country with space on 
their hands who would love to fill it with a nordstrom store 
