<TEXT>
despite all the dark forecasts that surging 
interest rates in japan and west germany will drive us rates up 
american corporations dependent on borrowed money show little sign 
of worry 
indeed if their propensity to borrow is a good indicator it 
appears that many companies regard the recent upturn in us rates 
to be temporary and not the beginning of an upward worldwide spiral 
that would be good news for the credit markets which have been 
gripped in recent weeks by fears about foreign demand for us 
treasury bonds and the sorry state of the junk bond market 
in the first two months of this year borrowers issued a total 
of 97 billion in investmentgrade bonds in the public market 
according to moodys investors service that amounts to an 
annualized rate of just under 60 billion a drop of more than 22 
percent from the 1989 total of 778 billion 
whats more this years total has been inflated by more issues 
from foreign borrowers such as the canadian province of nova 
scotia which offered 300 million of 30year bonds this past week 
the surprising upturn in longterm bond yields in early 1990 
definitely has discouraged a significant amount of investmentgrade 
corporate bond issuance says john lonski senior economist at 
moodys 
many a corporate treasurer perhaps still expects longterm 
bond yields to decline later in the year he said 
while corporations have been abstaining from the bond market 
they have been actively peddling ious in shortterm markets where 
rates havent risen as much the total amount of commercial paper 
outstanding issued by nonfinancial companies was 1365 billion as 
of feb 21 a jump of 831 billion since the start of the year 
seth waugh managing director in charge of corporate bond 
trading and new issues at merrill lynch amp co said most wall 
street bankers had thought rates would stay low and bond business 
would boom in the first quarter 
instead rates have risen because of a spurt in inflation a 
belief that the economy is on the mend and fears of more intense 
competition for global investment funds from japan and west germany 
the yield on the treasurys benchmark 30year bond has risen 
from a december low of near 78 percent to around 86 percent 
currently 
waugh says a pickup in new issues in the past two weeks shows 
some corporations want to lock in current rates to guard against an 
increase even though many others are content to wait a 
quarterpoint move in interest rates would produce a rush of 
borrowings he predicts motivated by fear if rates go up or by the 
cheaper cost of funds if rates go down 
its a pretty divided camp right now he says 
analysts say its far too soon to read anything deeper into the 
decline in borrowings nevertheless lonski says there are several 
reasons to suspect that corporate activity might stay subdued 
the sluggish economy has slowed growth in capital spending 
reducing companies borrowing needs he says also the collapse of 
the junk bond market as a source of takeover financing has taken 
some pressure off corporate managers he says 
there is less of a need to leverage the balance sheet in order 
to boost your stock price he says 
if thats true it would mark a stark change from the debthappy 
1980s moodys estimates net interest costs amounted to 42 percent 
of operating earnings for nonfinancial companies in last years 
third quarter up from 35 percent in 1988 and an average of 20 
percent from 1972 to 1982 
the rise in debt service largely reflected the explosive growth 
of the junk market today that market is extremely sluggish thanks 
to the collapse of junk prices and of drexel burnham lambert inc 
only 700 million in junk bonds have been issued so far this year 
vs more than 32 billion in all 1988 
a treasurer for the financing arm of one of the nations biggest 
companies says junk bond woes have turned investors off from even 
topgrade corporate bonds making it difficult to borrow this 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity said wall streets 
preoccupation with its internal problems also is to blame for the 
slump in borrowings 
i dont think the investment bankers in this country with 
their problems are as aggressive or as innovative or as ready to 
put their capital behind transactions he said 
