<TEXT>
an alderman is proposing an ordinance that would 
allow the city to use its power of eminent domain to prevent the 
shutdown of local manufacturing plants acquired in takeovers 
the proposed law forcing businesses to sell under city order 
would be the first of its kind in the nation although critics say 
it would amount to unconstitutional nationalization of 
companies 
what we trying to do is focus on corporate raiders buying 
plants on the edge of going under alderman bernard hansen said 
friday they say they are going to improve the plant and keep it 
going but instead they close them and take jobs to another 
country 
hansen said the proposed ordinance would protect jobs by giving 
chicagos economic development commissioner the right to invoke 
eminent domain against the owner of a manufacturing plant that is 
shutting down 
laws of eminent domain allow governments to seize property in 
matters of public interest 
under the proposed ordinance the city could force the sale of 
the seized plant if a buyer had been found to keep the plant open 
for business the ordinance would apply to plants closing within 
five years of takeover by a new owner 
the proposal was drafted by a group called business and 
professional people for the public interest on behalf of workers 
and community groups fighting to keep open a plant operated by 
stewartwarner corp 
the company which makes electronics equipment was purchased by 
britains btr plc which last year announced plans to shutter the 
plant in 1991 and move manufacturing operations to mexico 
hansen said there are potential buyers for the plant but that 
btr refuses to sell 
but critics say the ordinance would allow unwelcome intrusions 
by the city into corporate affairs 
this is a city equivalent of nationalizing a company said 
sam mitchell executive director of the chicago association of 
commerce and industry 
i can understand motivation of the ordinance to keep jobs in 
the city but i dont believe the city or any unit of government 
have the right to step into and effectively nationalize a company 
because they do something that doesnt please that government 
hansen who heads the chicago city councils ecomonic 
development committee said a hearing on the proposed ordinance is 
scheduled for later this month 
lester w brann president of the illinois state chamber of 
commerce calls the proposed ordinance a screwy idea 
the marketplace is going to determine where companies locate 
and where they expand their plants he said they are going to 
expand where the governments operate efficently where incentives 
are offered and taxes are low 
brann said the proposed ordinance could impose a new burden on 
taxpayers and said companies taken over by the city could run into 
problems before a new buyer is found 
the city council would be well advised to take a good hard 
look at what the city is or isnt doing to encourage business 
expansion he said adding that the proposal could be an 
unconstitutional interference with interstate commerce 
