<TEXT>
the fate of drexel burnham lambert inc was 
sealed not by 650 million in penalties agreed to pay to settle 
fraud charges but by the firms own investment strategy securities 
and exchange chairman richard c breeden says 
i dont think you can justifiably say that it was the money 
they had to pay in fines breeden told reporters friday after 
testifying before the senate banking housing and urban affairs 
committee 
breeden also said the sec is investigating the 
multimilliondollar bonuses drexel paid its employees before its 
collapse drexel has said it paid 260 million in bonuses in 
december and january but that the decision to make the payments 
came long before its financial woes became apparent 
on thursday a drexel lawyer told another congressional panel 
that the firm needed to pay big bonuses to retain professionals 
after the bad publicity and uncertainty following the plea bargain 
in december 1988 
if the bonuses were a dodge to reduce drexels assets before 
seeking bankruptcy protection then its possible well take some 
action breeden told the committee 
drexel once the nations fifthlargest securities firm 
collapsed in the wake of a sharp drop in the value of its 
highyield highrisk junk bond portfolio and its admission of 
securities law violations in a plea bargain with federal 
prosecutors 
the parent company sought protection from creditors under the 
federal bankruptcy law feb 13 after defaulting on 100 million in 
shortterm debt and failing to gain new loans to help stem a cash 
crisis 
the sec is seeking bankruptcy court certification as a drexel 
creditor because the firm still owes the government 150 million 
from the settlement while conceding drexel would have been a 
very different company had they not engaged in felony violations of 
us law breeden said the firms fate rested with its 
managements decisions 
drexel still had sizable cash and capital resources after 
pleading guilty to six felony counts and agreeing to the 650 
million settlement he said 
they could have tried to run a smaller firm they were 
unreasonably aggressive in maintaining a 28 billion balance sheet 
with the level of borrowing they had breeden said 
